
Q&A: Challenging Questions About This Book

Questions are not obstacles—they are invitations to think.

While reading this book, you may have already started to feel some doubt, confusion, or even disagreement.

That’s exactly what I hoped for—not for you to believe, but to think.

Below, I’ve gathered some common questions or challenges that readers might raise. I’ll try to respond with my current understanding—not as final answers, but as starting points for further reflection.

We’ll begin with more practical questions, and gradually move toward deeper philosophical ones.

If you have your own thoughts, questions, or ideas, I warmly welcome you to share them. That’s how real dialogue begins.Q1: If infinity is just a mental illusion, why is mathematical infinity (like π) so precise and consistent?

Response:
It’s true—mathematical infinity, like the infinite decimal expansion of π or the concept of infinite sets in set theory, is precise and logically consistent.

But Non-Infinity Theory sees this as part of an abstract logic system created by humans. It exists in the realm of concepts, not in physical reality.

Take the example of a “π-computer” from the book:
π can be calculated endlessly in theory, but in the physical world, time and energy are always limited. So we can only calculate part of it—never the full, “actual” infinity.

In short, the precision of mathematical infinity shows its value as a thinking tool, not as proof of how the universe truly works.

Q2: If the universe is a finite cycle, is there any scientific model that supports this idea?

Response:
Yes—modern cosmology does include some models that suggest the universe might not expand forever. Instead, it could go through cycles of expansion and contraction.

One example is the Big Bounce theory. It suggests that after the universe contracts to a certain point, it could “bounce back” and begin expanding again—similar to a new Big Bang.

This idea fits well with the book’s view of spiral time and the idea of the “π-computer reset.”

Such models show that the universe might be bounded by finite space and time, and that repeating cycles are a real possibility


Q3: Does Non-Infinity Theory reject the usefulness of mathematical infinity?

Response:
No, it doesn’t. Non-Infinity Theory does not deny the usefulness of mathematical infinity—it simply separates conceptual existence from physical reality.

Even in high-precision fields like bridge engineering, we only need a finite number of digits of π (pi) to get accurate results. There’s no need to “actually reach” infinity.

The idea of limits in calculus has driven huge progress in physics and engineering. But even these calculations always finish in a finite number of steps.

So yes, infinity in math is a powerful tool for thinking and modeling. Its value lies in helping us understand complex systems—not in proving that the universe is actually infinite.


Q4: If the universe resets in cycles, can consciousness or memory continue across them?

Response:
The π-computer example shows that consciousness and memory depend on physical carriers—like the brain or a computer chip.

If the universe resets back to “zero,” those carriers reset too. That means consciousness can’t continue in the same form from one cycle to the next.

In a finite universe, consciousness is a temporary phenomenon. It gets rebuilt with each cycle, not endlessly preserved. That’s why every moment and every choice matters deeply.


Q5: Does Non-Infinity Theory conflict with quantum mechanics, where probabilities seem infinite?

Response:
Quantum mechanics uses math to describe probabilities—like the many possible positions of an electron. These are infinite in theory, but not in actual physical outcomes.

As we saw in Chapter 2, even a still object (like a stone) has limited zero-point energy. So even though quantum math shows infinite possibilities, what we measure is always finite.

That means the “infinite” in quantum theory is a thinking tool, not a direct reflection of the real universe. Non-Infinity Theory is fully compatible with this view.


Q6: If infinity is an illusion, why do so many religions speak of ‘eternity’?

Response:
Non-Infinity Theory does not deny the value of religious belief or the deep comfort it gives people.

Ideas like eternal heaven, eternal hell, or eternal life are powerful because they help humans deal with fear, death, and the mystery of existence. These ideas bring meaning, purpose, and moral guidance—which are precious and deeply human.

Even if this universe is finite and cyclic, that doesn’t rule out the possibility of higher realities beyond our understanding—some of which may be infinite.

Religious “eternity” might be pointing to those higher levels of existence, or it may describe a kind of spiritual experience beyond space and time—not physical infinity.

From this view, the concepts of “non-infinite” and “eternity” don’t have to be in conflict. They might belong to different layers of reality.


Q7: Why do you think doing good is more likely to bring good results than bad results?

Response:
First, we need to understand that “good” is not an absolute idea. Different cultures, times, and personal experiences shape very different ideas of what “good” means. For some, following rules is good; for others, standing up against rules is good.

So let’s make it simple. Instead of talking about good and bad, imagine two actions: x and y.

If you give the world x, the chance that the world gives you back x is usually higher than the chance it gives you y. This is called a principle of reflection—what you put out tends to come back.

Apply this to emotions:
If you treat the world with hate, the world is more likely to respond with hate than with love.

It’s not punishment—it’s more like a mirror. How you treat the world shapes how it treats you.

Now, sometimes, you give kindness and get coldness back. That hurts, and you may stop being kind because you think it doesn’t work. But at that point, you’re choosing to bet on coldness.

Over time, these choices shape the kind of loop or system you end up living in. If more people bet on coldness, the system becomes colder.

So, what you choose to put out into the world is, in a way, choosing the kind of reality you want to be part of.


Q8: If infinity is just a thinking tool, why do people feel like it’s real?

Response:
People often feel that infinity is real because of the limits of our senses and mind. When we can’t see where something ends—like the edge of the universe—we tend to assume it goes on forever.

This feeling of infinity is less about truth and more about filling in the blanks. It gives us comfort in the face of the unknown.

But Non-Infinity Theory invites us to look closer at this mental habit and to consider that maybe the universe is not infinite, just hard to measure.


Q9: If the universe is limited, does that mean free will is limited too?

Response:
No. Free will doesn’t need infinite possibilities to matter.

In a finite space of choices, every decision you make becomes more meaningful—because it directly affects what happens next.

In fact, having too many options (as in infinity) can make your choices feel less important, like they don’t really change anything.

So, a finite universe doesn’t take away your freedom—it makes your freedom matter more.


Q10: If consciousness resets with the universe, what’s the point of life?

Response:
The meaning of life isn’t found in some final result or in lasting forever. It’s found in the value of what you do right now.

Even if the universe resets, your choices and actions still help shape a better structure for the next cycle.

Meaning isn’t something we “discover”—it’s something we create and give. And that’s what makes our finite lives rich and full, not meaningless.


Q11: Why do you say both “infinite” and “non-infinite” can be right and wrong at the same time? Isn’t that just saying nothing?

Response:
It might sound like a contradiction at first, but this idea actually helps us go beyond black-and-white thinking. It shows us that both “infinite” and “non-infinite” can make sense—depending on which level of reality we are talking about.

This isn’t avoiding the question—it’s pointing out that the meaning and truth of these ideas depend on the context.

1. Why can “infinite” be both right and wrong?
Right:
In abstract thinking (like math), or in our emotional experience when looking at the vast universe, “infinite” feels real and useful. It’s a mental tool or a way our mind imagines things.
 Wrong:
In the physical universe, we have no clear proof that anything is truly infinite. If we try to apply the idea of “infinity” directly to physical reality, it might be wrong. It could just be a reaction from our brain when it faces something too large to understand.

2. Why can “non-infinite” be both right and wrong?
 Right:
If we look at the cycles and limits in how the universe works, the idea that the universe is finite and repeating is logical and fits many observations.
 Wrong:
If we treat “non-infinite” as the final and only truth, that might also be wrong. Because even if our universe is finite, it could be part of a bigger system, one that our current knowledge cannot yet understand or measure.

“Infinite” and “non-infinite” are not simple yes/no answers.

They each have truth and limits depending on the level of reality we’re looking at.

It’s like looking at a painting. You can say it’s made of paint (true), or say it expresses fear (also true). Both views are real, just at different levels.

Understanding this helps us let go of the need for one absolute answer, and instead approach the universe with humility and openness.


Q12: Does Hilbert’s Hotel prove that infinity is logically real?

Response:
Hilbert’s Hotel is a famous math thought experiment. It shows how potential infinity works in logic—it’s internally consistent, and that’s impressive.

But this only works in abstract math, not in the physical world.

Like the π-computer example in this book, infinity always needs a finite system (like time or energy) to be expressed.

Hilbert’s Hotel proves how strong logical thinking can be—but it does not prove that physical infinity exists.


Q13: If infinity is an illusion, does that deny the idea of infinite artistic inspiration?

Response:
Not at all. Non-Infinity Theory does not deny the power or beauty of artistic inspiration.

Artistic creativity and the feeling of endless ideas are examples of how our finite minds can still produce vast imagination under specific conditions.

The example of the Oscar trophy in the book shows this clearly:
Some of the most meaningful creations come from working within limits. That’s what makes them special.

So, inspiration can feel infinite, even if it’s created in a finite system—and that’s the beauty of it

Q14: If something stops, why call it a “beginning” or a “repeat”? Isn’t that just a word trick?

Response:
It’s not a word trick. It’s a way of seeing things from a cyclical perspective.

Here’s the logic:
Our existence itself is proof that “nothingness” is not truly infinite.
If the universe had come from a truly infinite void, then “something” could never have appeared at all.

So that “nothingness” must be limited and changeable.

If even “nothing” has limits, then every end already holds the potential for a new start.

That’s why Non-Infinity Theory sees “stopping” not as a final end, but often as the gateway to restarting or repeating.



Q15: Your book uses a lot of poker and gambling examples to explain philosophy. Are you promoting gambling?

Response:
Absolutely not. I’m not encouraging anyone to gamble.

I use examples from gambling because a game of chance is built on probability and decision-making—which are also at the heart of how the universe works and how we make life choices.

Uncertainty, statistics, psychology, and risk—all present in gambling—also reflect how we deal with real-world decisions.

Instead of using complex math or abstract physics, I use casino examples because they are familiar and easy to understand for most people. They help show how deep structures hide inside everyday choices.

Personally, I’m not a gambler. I’ve never had any addiction or fantasy about it.

To be honest, sitting at a gambling table too long makes me bored. The repetitive actions and mechanical betting don’t appeal to me.

What truly interests me isn’t winning or losing—it’s the logic and human behavior behind the game.

So the casino is just a metaphor. I use it as a mirror to reflect how every life decision is like placing a bet—but what we’re betting isn’t money. It’s our energy, mindset, and values.


Q16: Since you focus on “non-infinity,” why not just call it “finite theory”? Doesn’t “non-infinity” sound confusing or redundant?

Response:
At first, “non-infinity” may sound like just another way of saying “finite.” But actually, they are not the same thing.

The word “finite” usually makes people think of something small, countable, or limited by borders.

But in this book, “non-infinity” is used to break free from binary thinking—to question our deep belief in infinity itself.

We often think: “If something is not infinite, it must be finite.”
But this either/or logic is exactly what Non-Infinity Theory challenges.

For example, imagine a system that’s so vast we can’t see its edges, or one that keeps reshaping itself endlessly. Is that really “finite”? Or is it something else—something non-infinite, but not simply limited?

This book suggests that instead of jumping to label the universe as “finite,” we should pause and ask why we believe so easily in infinity. Is “infinite” just a product of our math and language, rather than something truly real?

So “non-infinity” is a deliberate choice. It means:
I reject the idea that infinity is real, but I don’t want to replace it with another extreme.

This term leaves space to explore things like cycles, iterations, and systems that are predictable but never fully completed—things that are neither infinite nor strictly limited.


Q17: What if “nothingness” has no time at all?

Response:
This leads to a deep paradox — if true nothingness has no time, then nothing can ever start or end. But here we are — we exist. That means:
Nothingness didn’t last forever. At some point, it ended. That’s how the universe could begin.

So the fact that “I exist” is already a denial of infinite nothingness.
If nothingness had no end, then this moment — you reading this, me writing it — could never have happened.

The end of “nothing” is the beginning of time. No language or philosophy can avoid this truth.
